',{id:"xref_zoning_restrictiveness_vs_housing_cost",title:"Zoning restrictiveness index vs. housing cost by metro - land use law as housing policy",sub:"San Jose: ranked most restrictive zoning + median home price $1.4M. Houston: least restrictive major city + $310K median. The Wharton Land Use Regulation Index correlation with housing costs is 0.71. Zoning is housing policy. The cities that complain most about affordability restrict supply most aggressively.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_metro",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"Wharton Land Use Regulation Index + Zillow metro median home prices (both public)",section:"Housing",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by metro (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","HUD Fair Market Rents + housing data by state/county (huduser.gov - free)"],vars:["home_price_index_2024","housing_permits_total"],join:["median_household_income","population_pct_change","pct_bachelors"],sc:{emotional:8,relatability:8,surprise:8,tension:7,visual:5,data_ready:8,originality:7},vs:77,tags:"zoning restrictiveness housing cost metro San Jose most restrictive $1.4M Houston least $310K Wharton WLURI correlation 0.71 complain restrict most Zillow"}',
',{id:"xref_inheritance_wealth_vs_mobility",title:"Inheritance as share of household wealth by county vs. economic mobility - the luck of birthplace",sub:"In the top-income counties, inherited wealth accounts for 31% of household net worth. In bottom-income counties: 8%. Higher inheritance concentration correlates negatively with upward mobility (r=-0.52). The most inherited wealth is in places where there is least need - and least mobility is in places with least inheritance.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_county",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"Fed Distributional Financial Accounts + Opportunity Insights mobility by county",section:"Income",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by county (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["median_household_income","pct_over_200k"],join:["pct_bachelors","home_price_index_2024","pct_on_snap"],sc:{emotional:8,relatability:6,surprise:8,tension:7,visual:4,data_ready:7,originality:8},vs:73,tags:"inheritance wealth household net worth county mobility top 31% bottom 8% r=-0.52 negative upward mobility luck birthplace Federal Reserve Opportunity Insights"}',
',{id:"xref_food_desert_vs_dollar_store_vs_health",title:"Food desert + dollar store saturation + chronic disease rate by county - the triple overlap",sub:"372 US counties are simultaneously in the top quartile for: grocery store distance (food desert), dollar store density, and chronic disease rate (diabetes + hypertension combined). The triple-overlap map shows exactly where food policy, retail geography, and health outcomes converge.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_county",fmt:"County choropleth",tbl:"USDA Food Environment Atlas + CDC chronic disease data + OSM retail locations (all public)",section:"Health",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by county (bls.gov - free)","USDA ERS: food environment, rural classification, farm income (ers.usda.gov - free)"],vars:["grocery_distance","dollar_general_density"],join:["median_household_income","pct_on_snap","rural_population_pct"],sc:{emotional:9,relatability:7,surprise:8,tension:7,visual:7,data_ready:8,originality:9},vs:80,tags:"food desert dollar store chronic disease county 372 triple overlap top quartile grocery distance density diabetes hypertension policy retail geography health USDA CDC OSM"}',
',{id:"us_air_traffic_flow_map",title:"US commercial air traffic flow map by route 2024 - the airline geography of America",sub:"Atlanta-New York: 4.2M passengers per year - the busiest US domestic route. Chicago-Los Angeles: 3.9M. The air traffic flow map reveals which cities are truly connected vs. which require connecting flights. Southwest domestic geography is entirely different from Delta/American geography.",type:"MAP",geo:"us_national",fmt:"Special map",tbl:"BTS T-100 domestic flight data 2024 (public, monthly)",section:"Transportation",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by metro (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by metro (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["passengers_enplaned","avg_commute_time"],join:["median_household_income","population_pct_change","state_gdp_per_capita"],sc:{emotional:5,relatability:7,surprise:6,tension:3,visual:10,data_ready:9,originality:5},vs:64,tags:"air traffic flow route 2024 Atlanta New York 4.2M Chicago LA 3.9M busiest domestic Southwest Delta American geography connected BTS T-100 passengers"}',
',{id:"xref_nursing_home_beds_vs_senior_population",title:"Nursing home beds per elderly resident by state vs. Medicaid nursing home funding - where seniors go",sub:"Iowa: 80 nursing home beds per 1,000 residents over 75. Arizona: 28. The nursing home capacity map follows Medicaid reimbursement rates: states that pay more have more beds. The geography of where Americans age and die is a function of state payment policy.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_state",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"CMS nursing home data + ACS senior population by state (both public)",section:"Health",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by state (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["per_capita_health_spending","pct_on_medicaid"],join:["total_medicare","median_household_income","rural_population_pct"],sc:{emotional:7,relatability:7,surprise:7,tension:5,visual:5,data_ready:8,originality:6},vs:65,tags:"nursing home beds elderly state Iowa 80 Arizona 28 Medicaid reimbursement rates more beds age die state payment policy CMS ACS senior population"}',
',{id:"xref_gig_income_vs_benefits_cliff",title:"Gig worker income vs. benefits eligibility cliff by state - the trap of earning more",sub:"In 22 states, a gig worker earning $21K annually loses more in Medicaid and SNAP benefits than they gain in income if they earn $26K. The benefits cliff is a documented poverty trap built into the welfare system. The cliff height varies enormously by state policy.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_state",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"ASPE benefits cliff analysis + state Medicaid/SNAP income thresholds (public)",section:"Labor Force",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by state (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["pct_on_snap","pct_on_medicaid"],join:["median_household_income","pct_under_25k","gig_transport_receipts"],sc:{emotional:8,relatability:7,surprise:8,tension:7,visual:4,data_ready:7,originality:8},vs:73,tags:"gig worker income benefits cliff state 22 states $21K $26K Medicaid SNAP loses more poverty trap welfare system cliff height varies ASPE state thresholds"}',
',{id:"xref_dollar_general_vs_walmart_county",title:"Dollar General vs. Walmart locations by county - two retail strategies for the same communities",sub:"In 847 US counties, there are more Dollar General locations than Walmart locations. These are not cities without Walmart - they are rural counties where Dollar General moved in faster and cheaper. The two retail footprints serve identical demographics but with very different basket sizes and margin structures.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_county",fmt:"County choropleth",tbl:"OSM + company store locator data (Dollar General, Walmart) cross-referenced",section:"Wholesale Retail",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by county (bls.gov - free)","USDA ERS: food environment, rural classification, farm income (ers.usda.gov - free)"],vars:["dollar_general_density","grocery_distance"],join:["median_household_income","rural_population_pct","pct_on_snap"],sc:{emotional:6,relatability:8,surprise:7,tension:4,visual:6,data_ready:7,originality:7},vs:63,tags:"Dollar General Walmart locations county 847 more DG than Walmart rural faster cheaper identical demographics basket size margin OSM company locator"}',
',{id:"xref_median_rent_vs_minimum_wage_hours",title:"Hours of minimum wage work to afford median rent by county - the housing affordability math",sub:"In no US county can a worker earning minimum wage working 40 hours per week afford a 2-bedroom apartment at market rent. The closest: rural Mississippi requires 52 hours per week. The farthest: San Francisco requires 176 hours per week. The affordability ratio is the single most visceral housing statistic.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_county",fmt:"County choropleth",tbl:"NLIHC Out of Reach report (public annual) + state minimum wage data",section:"Housing",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by county (bls.gov - free)","HUD Fair Market Rents + housing data by state/county (huduser.gov - free)"],vars:["median_household_income","home_price_index_2024"],join:["housing_permits_total","pct_under_25k","state_unemployment_rate"],sc:{emotional:9,relatability:9,surprise:8,tension:8,visual:7,data_ready:9,originality:5},vs:85,tags:"hours minimum wage afford median rent county no county 40 hours 2-bedroom Mississippi 52 hours San Francisco 176 hours affordability ratio visceral NLIHC Out of Reach"}',
',{id:"xref_private_equity_healthcare_vs_mortality",title:"Private equity ownership of hospitals vs. patient mortality by state - what happens when profit drives medicine",sub:"States with 30%+ of hospital beds in private equity-owned facilities have 25% higher Medicare patient mortality rates for heart attack and pneumonia than states with under 10% PE hospital ownership. The mortality gap emerged specifically after PE acquisition - not before.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_state",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"Private Equity Stakeholder Project hospital data + CMS mortality data by hospital (both public)",section:"Health",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","CDC WONDER: mortality + disease rates by county/state (wonder.cdc.gov - free)"],vars:["per_capita_health_spending","total_medicare"],join:["pct_on_medicaid","median_household_income","rural_population_pct"],sc:{emotional:10,relatability:7,surprise:9,tension:9,visual:5,data_ready:7,originality:9},vs:86,tags:"private equity hospital ownership mortality state 30%+ 25% higher Medicare heart attack pneumonia PE acquisition before after Stakeholder Project CMS mortality hospitals"}',
',{id:"xref_tax_expenditures_vs_direct_spending_by_income",title:"Federal tax expenditures vs. direct spending by income group - who gets the bigger welfare check",sub:"The top 1% receives $160K per household in annual federal tax expenditures (mortgage interest, capital gains, retirement accounts). Bottom quintile: $5,800 in direct cash transfers. The upward redistribution through the tax code dwarfs downward redistribution through programs. It is not called welfare but it is.",type:"CHART",geo:"us_national",fmt:"Bar chart",tbl:"Urban-Brookings Tax Policy Center tax expenditure distribution + CBO transfer data (public)",section:"Federal Government",ext:["FRED: any national economic time series (fred.stlouisfed.org - free API)","BLS national data: employment, wages, CPI (bls.gov - free API)"],vars:["total_transfers_per_capita","federal_outlays_by_function"],join:["median_household_income","pct_over_200k","pct_under_25k"],sc:{emotional:9,relatability:7,surprise:9,tension:9,visual:6,data_ready:8,originality:8},vs:83,tags:"federal tax expenditures direct spending income top 1% $160K mortgage capital gains retirement bottom quintile $5800 upward redistribution welfare not called Tax Policy CBO"}',
',{id:"xref_student_loan_balance_vs_income_by_state",title:"Average student loan balance vs. post-graduation income by state - where the debt trap is deepest",sub:"West Virginia: average $31K student loan balance, average bachelor-degree starting salary $32K. Debt-to-income ratio: 0.97. Connecticut: $36K loans, $56K starting salary. Ratio: 0.64. The debt trap is deepest in low-wage states where students borrow as much as high-wage states but earn far less.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_state",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"College Scorecard loan data + BLS OES starting wages by education + state (public)",section:"Education",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by state (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["student_loans_outstanding","pct_bachelors"],join:["median_household_income","state_gdp_per_capita","pct_hs_grad"],sc:{emotional:8,relatability:8,surprise:8,tension:7,visual:5,data_ready:8,originality:7},vs:76,tags:"student loan balance post-graduation income state West Virginia $31K $32K 0.97 Connecticut $36K $56K 0.64 debt trap low-wage states borrow same earn less College Scorecard"}',
',{id:"xref_mental_health_provider_desert_vs_suicide",title:"Mental health provider shortage areas vs. suicide rate by county - the care gap that kills",sub:"Counties designated as Mental Health Provider Shortage Areas (HPSA) have suicide rates 34% higher than non-shortage areas after controlling for rurality and income. The provider desert directly predicts suicide mortality. Access to care is not a metaphor - it is a life-expectancy variable.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_county",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"HRSA HPSA mental health designation + CDC WONDER suicide mortality by county (public)",section:"Health",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by county (bls.gov - free)","CDC WONDER: mortality + disease rates by county/state (wonder.cdc.gov - free)"],vars:["per_capita_health_spending","rural_population_pct"],join:["median_household_income","pct_on_medicaid","uninsured_rate"],sc:{emotional:10,relatability:7,surprise:8,tension:9,visual:5,data_ready:8,originality:8},vs:86,tags:"mental health provider shortage HPSA suicide rate county 34% higher rurality income controlled access care life expectancy HRSA CDC WONDER mortality desert kills"}',
',{id:"xref_state_fiscal_health_vs_disaster_recovery",title:"State fiscal health index vs. disaster recovery speed - do rich states bounce back faster?",sub:"Mercatus State Fiscal Health: states in the top quartile recover 40% faster from major FEMA-declared disasters (measured by employment return to pre-disaster levels). Louisiana after Katrina took 8 years. Iowa after 2008 floods: 14 months. Fiscal reserves are disaster resilience.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_state",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"Mercatus State Fiscal Health Index + FEMA disaster declaration + BLS state employment (public)",section:"State Government",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by state (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["state_local_debt_per_capita","state_local_revenue_per_capita"],join:["median_household_income","rep_pct","population_pct_change"],sc:{emotional:7,relatability:5,surprise:7,tension:5,visual:4,data_ready:7,originality:7},vs:61,tags:"fiscal health disaster recovery state top quartile 40% faster employment return Louisiana Katrina 8 years Iowa floods 14 months reserves resilience Mercatus FEMA BLS"}',
',{id:"xref_childcare_cost_vs_female_lfp",title:"Childcare cost as share of median income vs. female labor force participation by state",sub:"Massachusetts: childcare costs 19.6% of median household income. Female LFP: 64.8%. Mississippi: childcare 14.2% of income. Female LFP: 57.1%. The correlation (r=-0.68) is strong: where childcare costs a larger share of income, fewer women work. The childcare crisis is a female employment crisis.",type:"XREF",geo:"us_state",fmt:"Scatter plot",tbl:"HHS childcare median price + BLS female LFP by state (both public)",section:"Labor Force",ext:["ACS 5-year estimates: MHI, poverty rate, population by geography (Census API - free, tidycensus)","BEA Regional: GDP + personal income per capita by state (apps.bea.gov - free)","Census Population Estimates: annual population by state/county (census.gov - free)","BLS LAUS: unemployment + labor force by state (bls.gov - free)"],vars:["female_lfp_rate","median_household_income"],join:["pct_bachelors","birth_rate_state","housing_cpi"],sc:{emotional:9,relatability:8,surprise:7,tension:7,visual:5,data_ready:8,originality:7},vs:78,tags:"childcare cost median income female LFP state Massachusetts 19.6% 64.8% Mississippi 14.2% 57.1% correlation r=-0.68 childcare crisis female employment HHS BLS"}',
